[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] In linear algebra, **Cramer's rule** is an explicit formula for the solution of a system of linear equations with as many equations as unknowns, valid whenever the system has a unique solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] It expresses the solution in terms of the determinants of the (square) coefficient matrix and of matrices obtained from it by replacing one column by the column vector of right-sides of the equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] It is named after Gabriel Cramer, who published the rule for an arbitrary number of unknowns in 1750, although Colin Maclaurin also published special cases of the rule in 1748, and possibly knew of it as early as 1729.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] where the *n* × *n* matrix A has a nonzero determinant, and the vector $\mathbf {x} =(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})^{\mathsf {T}}$ is the column vector of the variables.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] where $A_{i}$ is the matrix formed by replacing the i-th column of A by the column vector **b**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] where the *n* × *n* matrix A has a nonzero determinant, and X, B are *n* × *m* matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Let $A_{B}(I,J)$ be the *n* × *n* matrix formed by replacing the $i_{s}$ column of A by the $j_{s}$ column of B, for all $s=1,\ldots ,k$ .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] In the case $k=1$ , this reduces to the normal Cramer's rule.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] The rule holds for systems of equations with coefficients and unknowns in any field, not just in the real numbers.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] The proof for Cramer's rule uses the following properties of the determinants: linearity with respect to any given column and the fact that the determinant is zero whenever two columns are equal, which is implied by the property that the sign of the determinant flips if you switch two columns.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Fix the index *j* of a column, and consider that the entries of the other columns have fixed values.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] This makes the determinant a function of the entries of the jth column.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] where the $C_{i,j}$ are coefficients that depend on the entries of A that are not in column j.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] If the function $D_{j}$ is applied to any *other* column *k* of A, then the result is the determinant of the matrix obtained from A by replacing column *j* by a copy of column *k*, so the resulting determinant is 0 (the case of two equal columns).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] As, by construction, the numerator is the determinant of the matrix obtained from A by replacing column *j* by **b**, we get the expression of Cramer's rule as a necessary condition for a solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] It remains to prove that these values for the unknowns form a solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Let M be the *n* × *n* matrix that has the coefficients of $D_{j}$ as jth row, for $j=1,\ldots ,n$ (this is the adjugate matrix for A).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] This completes the proof, since a left inverse of a square matrix is also a right-inverse (see Invertible matrix theorem).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Let A be an *n* × *n* matrix with entries in a field *F*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] where adj(*A*) denotes the adjugate matrix, det(*A*) is the determinant, and *I* is the identity matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] This gives a formula for the inverse of A, provided det(*A*) ≠ 0.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] In fact, this formula works whenever *F* is a commutative ring, provided that det(*A*) is a unit.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] If det(*A*) is not a unit, then A is not invertible over the ring (it may be invertible over a larger ring in which some non-unit elements of F may be invertible).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] The rules for 3 × 3 matrices are similar.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Cramer's rule is used in the Ricci calculus in various calculations involving the Christoffel symbols of the first and second kind.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] In particular, Cramer's rule can be used to prove that the divergence operator on a Riemannian manifold is invariant with respect to change of coordinates.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] We give a direct proof, suppressing the role of the Christoffel symbols.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Let $(M,g)$ be a Riemannian manifold equipped with local coordinates $(x^{1},x^{2},\dots ,x^{n})$ .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] We use the summation convention throughout.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] is invariant under change of coordinates.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] An equation for ${\dfrac {\partial x}{\partial u}}$ can be found by applying Cramer's rule.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Cramer's rule can be used to prove that an integer programming problem whose constraint matrix is totally unimodular and whose right-hand side is integer, has integer basic solutions.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] This makes the integer program substantially easier to solve.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Cramer's rule is used to derive the general solution to an inhomogeneous linear differential equation by the method of variation of parameters.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Cramer's rule has a geometric interpretation that can be considered also a proof or simply giving insight about its geometric nature.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] These geometric arguments work in general and not only in the case of two equations with two unknowns presented here.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] In general, when there are more variables and equations, the determinant of n vectors of length n will give the *volume* of the *parallelepiped* determined by those vectors in the n-th dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Therefore, the area of the parallelogram determined by $x_{1}{\binom {a_{11}}{a_{21}}}$ and ${\binom {a_{12}}{a_{22}}}$ has to be $x_{1}$ times the area of the first one since one of the sides has been multiplied by this factor.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] This is a restatement of the proof above in abstract language.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Consider the map $\mathbf {x} =(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})\mapsto {\frac {1}{\det A}}\left(\det(A_{1}),\ldots ,\det(A_{n})\right),$ where $A_{i}$ is the matrix A with $\mathbf {x}$ substituted in the i th column, as in Cramer's rule.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Because of linearity of determinant in every column, this map is linear.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Observe that it sends the i th column of A to the i th basis vector $\mathbf {e} _{i}=(0,\ldots ,1,\ldots ,0)$ (with 1 in the i th place), because determinant of a matrix with a repeated column is 0.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] So we have a linear map which agrees with the inverse of A on the column space; hence it agrees with $A^{-1}$ on the span of the column space.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Since A is invertible, the column vectors span all of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , so our map really is the inverse of A .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] On the other hand, assuming that our original matrix A is invertible, this matrix $X_{1}$ has columns $A^{-1}\mathbf {b} ,A^{-1}\mathbf {v} _{2},\ldots ,A^{-1}\mathbf {v} _{n}$ , where $\mathbf {v} _{n}$ is the *n*-th column of the matrix A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] A system of equations is said to be inconsistent when there are no solutions and it is called indeterminate when there is more than one solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] For linear equations, an indeterminate system will have infinitely many solutions (if it is over an infinite field), since the solutions can be expressed in terms of one or more parameters that can take arbitrary values.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Cramer's rule applies to the case where the coefficient determinant is nonzero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] In the 2×2 case, if the coefficient determinant is zero, then the system is inconsistent if the numerator determinants are nonzero, or indeterminate if the numerator determinants are zero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] By inspection, the second equation is a multiple of the first, so there are infinitely many solutions.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] which both have zero numerators and denominators, meaning the system has infinitely many solutions and is therefore indeterminate.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] By inspection, the left hand side of both equations are identical, with different right hand sides.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Therefore, the system is inconsistent, meaning there are no solutions.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] which are both undefined due to division by zero, however the non-zero numerators means the system has no solutions and is therefore inconsistent.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] For 3×3 or higher systems, the only thing one can say when the coefficient determinant equals zero is that if any of the numerator determinants are nonzero, then the system must be inconsistent.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] However, having all determinants zero does not imply that the system is indeterminate.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] A simple example where all determinants vanish (equal zero) but the system is still inconsistent is the 3×3 system *x*+*y*+*z*=1, *x*+*y*+*z*=2, *x*+*y*+*z*=3.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Cramer's rule, implemented in a naive way, is computationally inefficient for systems of more than two or three equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] In the case of n equations in n unknowns, it requires computation of *n* + 1 determinants, while Gaussian elimination produces the result with the same (up to a constant factor independent of ⁠ n ⁠) computational complexity as the computation of a single determinant.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Moreover, the Bareiss algorithm is a simple modification of Gaussian elimination that produces in a single computation a matrix whose nonzero entries are the determinants involved in Cramer's rule.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] In 1983, an algorithm for solving the system using Cramer's rule in $n^{3}+O(n^{2})$ operations was proposed.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] This algorithm can use permutations exactly like those in the Gaussian method.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] Therefore, if approximate calculation methods are used, the solution will be more stable than the solution using the Gaussian method, since the first steps are calculated without error, before rounding off the numbers.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] In 1991, an algorithm with complexity of $n^{3}/2+O(n^{2})$ operations was published. .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] In 1997, an algorithm for solving a system using Cramer's rule with complexity equal to that of matrix multiplication was proposed..
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] For example, for the Strassen's Multiplication Algorithm, this algorithm computes the solution in $(7/15)n^{\log _{2}(7)}+O(n^{2})$ operations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/cramer-s-rule] with no tools other than a hand calculator, applying Cramer's Rule would provide the solution quite efficiently.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] In mathematics, **Gaussian elimination**, also known as **row reduction**, is an algorithm for solving systems of linear equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] It consists of a sequence of row-wise operations performed on the corresponding matrix of coefficients.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] This method can also be used to compute the rank of a matrix, the determinant of a square matrix, and the inverse of an invertible matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The method is named after Carl Friedrich Gauss (1777–1855).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] To perform row reduction on a matrix, one uses a sequence of elementary row operations to modify the matrix until the lower left-hand corner of the matrix is filled with zeros, as much as possible.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] This final form is unique; in other words, it is independent of the sequence of row operations used.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Using row operations to convert a matrix into reduced row echelon form is sometimes called **Gauss–Jordan elimination**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] In this case, the term *Gaussian elimination* refers to the process until it has reached its upper triangular, (unreduced) row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] For computational reasons, when solving systems of linear equations, it is sometimes preferable to stop row operations before the matrix is completely reduced.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The process of row reduction makes use of elementary row operations, and can be divided into two parts.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The first part (sometimes called forward elimination) reduces a given system to row echelon form, from which one can tell whether there are no solutions, a unique solution, or infinitely many solutions.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The second part (sometimes called back substitution) continues to use row operations until the solution is found; in other words, it puts the matrix into reduced row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Another point of view, which turns out to be very useful to analyze the algorithm, is that row reduction produces a matrix decomposition of the original matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The elementary row operations may be viewed as the multiplication on the left of the original matrix by elementary matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Alternatively, a sequence of elementary operations that reduces a single row may be viewed as multiplication by a Frobenius matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Then the first part of the algorithm computes an LU decomposition, while the second part writes the original matrix as the product of a uniquely determined invertible matrix and a uniquely determined reduced row echelon matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Adding a scalar multiple of one row to another.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] If the matrix is associated to a system of linear equations, then these operations do not change the solution set.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Therefore, if one's goal is to solve a system of linear equations, then using these row operations could make the problem easier.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] For each row in a matrix, if the row does not consist of only zeros, then the leftmost nonzero entry is called the *leading entry* (or *pivot*) of that row.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] If two leading entries are in the same column, then a row operation of type 3 can be used to make one of those entries zero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Then by using the row swapping operation, one can always order the rows so that for every non-zero row, the leading entry is to the right of the leading entry of the row above.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] If this is the case, the matrix is said to be in *row echelon form*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] In this form, the lower left part of the matrix contains only zeros, and all of the zero rows are below the non-zero rows.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The word "echelon" is used here because one can roughly think of the rows being ranked by their size, with the largest being at the top and the smallest being at the bottom.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] It is in echelon form because the zero row is at the bottom and the leading entry of the second row (in the third column) is to the right of the leading entry of the first row (in the second column).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The table below is the row reduction process applied simultaneously to the system of equations and its associated augmented matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] In practice, one does not usually deal with the systems in terms of equations, but instead makes use of the augmented matrix, which is more suitable for computer manipulations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The row reduction procedure may be summarized as follows: eliminate x from all equations below *L*1, and then eliminate y from all equations below *L*2.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] This will put the system into triangular form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Then, using back-substitution, each unknown can be solved for.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The second column describes which row operations have just been performed.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] For the first step, x is eliminated from *L*2 by adding ⁠3/2⁠*L*1 to *L*2.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Next, x is eliminated from *L*3 by adding *L*1 to *L*3.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Once y is also eliminated from the third row, the result is a system of linear equations in triangular form, and so the first part of the algorithm is complete.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] From a computational point of view, it is faster to solve the variables in reverse order, a process known as back-substitution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] In particular, there is a unique solution to the original system of equations in this case.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Instead of stopping once the matrix is in row echelon form, one could continue until the matrix is in *reduced* row echelon form, as it is done in the table.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The process of row reducing until the matrix is reduced is sometimes referred to as Gauss–Jordan elimination, to distinguish it from stopping after reaching echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The method of Gaussian elimination appears – albeit without proof – in the Chinese mathematical text Chapter Eight: *Rectangular Arrays* of *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Its use is illustrated in eighteen problems, with two to five equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The first reference to the book by this title is dated to 179 AD, but parts of it were written as early as approximately 150 BC.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] It was commented on by Liu Hui in the 3rd century.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] According to Grcar solution of linear equations by elimination was invented independently in several cultures in Eurasia starting from antiquity and in Europe definite examples of procedure were published already by late Renaissance (in 1550's).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] It is quite possible that already then the procedure was considered by mathematicians elementary and in no need to explanation for professionals, so we may never learn its detailed history except that by then it was practiced in at least several places in Europe.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The method in Europe stems from the notes of Isaac Newton.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] In 1669–1670, Newton wrote that all the algebra books known to him lacked a lesson for solving simultaneous equations, which Newton then supplied.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Cambridge University eventually published the notes as *Arithmetica Universalis* in 1707 long after Newton had left academic life.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The notes were widely imitated, which made (what is now called) Gaussian elimination a standard lesson in algebra textbooks by the end of the 18th century.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Carl Friedrich Gauss in 1810 devised a notation for symmetric elimination that was adopted in the 19th century by professional hand computers to solve the normal equations of least-squares problems.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The algorithm that is taught in high school was named for Gauss only in the 1950s as a result of confusion over the history of the subject.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Some authors use the term *Gaussian elimination* to refer only to the procedure until the matrix is in echelon form, and use the term Gauss–Jordan elimination to refer to the procedure which ends in reduced echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The name is used because it is a variation of Gaussian elimination as described by Wilhelm Jordan in 1888.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] However, the method also appears in an article by Clasen published in the same year.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Jordan and Clasen probably discovered Gauss–Jordan elimination independently.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Historically, the first application of the row reduction method is for solving systems of linear equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Below are some other important applications of the algorithm.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] If Gaussian elimination applied to a square matrix A produces a row echelon matrix B, let d be the product of the scalars by which the determinant has been multiplied, using the above rules.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Even on the fastest computers, these two methods are impractical or almost impracticable for *n* above 20.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] A variant of Gaussian elimination called **Gauss–Jordan elimination** can be used for finding the inverse of a matrix, if it exists.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] If *A* is an *n* × *n* square matrix, then one can use row reduction to compute its inverse matrix, if it exists.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] First, the *n* × *n* identity matrix is augmented to the right of *A*, forming an *n* × 2*n* block matrix [*A* | *I*].
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Now through application of elementary row operations, find the reduced echelon form of this *n* × 2*n* matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The matrix *A* is invertible if and only if it can be reduced to the identity matrix *I*; in this case the right block of the final matrix is *A*−1.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] If the algorithm is unable to reduce the left block to *I*, then *A* is not invertible.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] One can think of each row operation as the left product by an elementary matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] On the right, we see on the right that the product of these elementary matrices is *B* (since *B* = *BI*).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Meanwhile, on the left, we see that the effect of left multiplying the product of these matrices into *A* yields the identity matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Therefore *B* = *A*−1, the inverse desired.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] This procedure for finding the inverse works for square matrices of any size.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The Gaussian elimination algorithm can be applied to any *m* × *n* matrix A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] All of this applies also to the reduced row echelon form, which is a particular row echelon format.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The number of arithmetic operations required to perform row reduction is one way of measuring the algorithm's computational efficiency.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Thus it has a *arithmetic complexity* (time complexity, where each arithmetic operation takes one unit of time, independently of the size of the inputs) of O(*n*3).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] This complexity is a good measure of the time needed for the whole computation when the time for each arithmetic operation is approximately constant.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] This is the case when the coefficients are represented by floating-point numbers or when they belong to a finite field.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] If the coefficients are integers or rational numbers exactly represented, the intermediate entries can grow exponentially large, so the bit complexity is exponential.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] However, the Bareiss algorithm is a variant of Gaussian elimination that avoids this exponential growth of the intermediate entries; with the same arithmetic complexity of O(*n*3), it has a bit complexity of O(*n*5), and has therefore a strongly-polynomial time complexity.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Gaussian elimination and its variants can be used on computers for systems with thousands of equations and unknowns.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] However, the cost becomes prohibitive for systems with millions of equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] These large systems are generally solved using iterative methods.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Specific methods exist for systems whose coefficients follow a regular pattern (see System of linear equations).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The first strongly-polynomial time algorithm for Gaussian elimination was published by Jack Edmonds in 1967.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Independently, and almost simultaneously, Erwin Bareiss discovered another algorithm, based on the following remark, which applies to a division-free variant of Gaussian elimination.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] In standard Gaussian elimination, one subtracts from each row $R_{i}$ below the pivot row $R_{k}$ a multiple of $R_{k}$ by $r_{i,k}/r_{k,k},$ where $r_{i,k}$ and $r_{k,k}$ are the entries in the pivot column of $R_{i}$ and $R_{k},$ respectively.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Bareiss variant consists, instead, of replacing $R_{i}$ with ${\textstyle {\frac {r_{k,k}R_{i}-r_{i,k}R_{k}}{r_{k-1,k-1}}}.}$ This produces a row echelon form that has the same zero entries as with the standard Gaussian elimination.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Bareiss' main remark is that each matrix entry generated by this variant is the determinant of a submatrix of the original matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] In particular, if one starts with integer entries, the divisions occurring in the algorithm are exact divisions resulting in integers.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Therefore, all intermediate entries and final entries are integers.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Moreover, Hadamard's inequality provides an upper bound on the absolute values of the intermediate and final entries, and thus a bit complexity of ${\tilde {O}}(n^{5}),$ using soft O notation.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Moreover, as an upper bound on the size of final entries is known, a complexity ${\tilde {O}}(n^{4})$ can be obtained with modular computation followed either by Chinese remaindering or Hensel lifting.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] One possible problem is numerical instability, caused by the possibility of dividing by very small numbers.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] If, for example, the leading coefficient of one of the rows is very close to zero, then to row-reduce the matrix, one would need to divide by that number.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] This means that any error which existed for the number that was close to zero would be amplified.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Gaussian elimination is numerically stable for diagonally dominant or positive-definite matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] For general matrices, Gaussian elimination is usually considered to be stable, when using partial pivoting, even though there are examples of stable matrices for which it is unstable.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Gaussian elimination can be performed over any field, not just the real numbers.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Buchberger's algorithm is a generalization of Gaussian elimination to systems of polynomial equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] This generalization depends heavily on the notion of a monomial order.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The choice of an ordering on the variables is already implicit in Gaussian elimination, manifesting as the choice to work from left to right when selecting pivot positions.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Computing the rank of a tensor of order greater than 2 is NP-hard.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Therefore, if P ≠ NP, there cannot be a polynomial time analog of Gaussian elimination for higher-order tensors (matrices are array representations of order-2 tensors).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] As explained above, Gaussian elimination transforms a given *m* × *n* matrix A into a matrix in row-echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] In the following pseudocode, `A[i, j]` denotes the entry of the matrix A in row i and column j with the indices starting from 1.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] The transformation is performed *in place*, meaning that the original matrix is lost for being eventually replaced by its row-echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] This algorithm differs slightly from the one discussed earlier, by choosing a pivot with largest absolute value.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Such a *partial pivoting* may be required if, at the pivot place, the entry of the matrix is zero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] In any case, choosing the largest possible absolute value of the pivot improves the numerical stability of the algorithm, when floating point is used for representing numbers.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/gaussian-elimination] Upon completion of this procedure the matrix will be in row echelon form and the corresponding system may be solved by back substitution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In numerical analysis and linear algebra, **lower–upper** (**LU**) **decomposition** or **factorization** factors a matrix as the product of a lower triangular matrix and an upper triangular matrix (see matrix multiplication and matrix decomposition).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The product sometimes includes a permutation matrix as well.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] LU decomposition can be viewed as the matrix form of Gaussian elimination.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Computers usually solve square systems of linear equations using LU decomposition, and it is also a key step when inverting a matrix or computing the determinant of a matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] It is also sometimes referred to as **LR** decomposition (factors into left and right triangular matrices).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The LU decomposition algorithm for general matrices was introduced by the Polish astronomer Tadeusz Banachiewicz in 1938.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] An **LU factorization** refers to expression of A into product of two factors – a lower triangular matrix L and an upper triangular matrix U such that *A* = *LU*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Sometimes factorization is impossible without prior reordering of A to prevent division by zero or uncontrolled growth of rounding errors.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Hence alternative expression becomes *PAQ* = *LU*, where in formal notation permutation matrix factors P and Q indicate permutation of rows (or columns) of A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In theory P (or Q) is obtained by permutations of rows (or columns) of the identity matrix; in practice the corresponding permutations are applied directly to rows (or columns) of A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Matrix A of side n has $n^{2}$ coefficients while two triangle matrices combined contain *n*(*n* + 1) coefficients, and therefore n coefficients of matrices LU are not independent.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The convention is to set L unitriangular, i.e. with all n main diagonal elements equal to one.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This demonstrates also, that operations on rows (e.g. pivoting) are equivalent to those on columns of a transposed matrix, and in general choice of row or column algorithm offers no advantage.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In the lower triangular matrix all elements above the main diagonal are zero, in the upper triangular matrix, all the elements below the diagonal are zero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Without a proper ordering or permutations in the matrix, the factorization may fail to materialize.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] For example, it is easy to verify (by expanding the matrix multiplication) that ${\textstyle a_{11}=\ell _{11}u_{11}}$ .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If ${\textstyle a_{11}=0}$ , then at least one of ${\textstyle \ell _{11}}$ and ${\textstyle u_{11}}$ has to be zero, which implies that either L or U is singular.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This is impossible if A is nonsingular (invertible).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In terms of operations, zeroing/elimination of remaining elements of first column of A involves division of ${\textstyle a_{21},a_{31}}$ with ${\textstyle a_{11}}$ , impossible if it is 0.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] It can be removed by simply reordering the rows of A so that the first element of the permuted matrix is nonzero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The same problem in subsequent factorization steps can be removed the same way.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] For numerical stability against rounding errors/division by small numbers it is important to select ${\textstyle a_{11}}$ of large absolute value (cf. pivoting).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The above example of 3 × 3 matrices demonstrates that matrix product of top row and leftmost columns of involved matrices plays special role for LU to succeed.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Let us mark consecutive versions of matrices with $(0),\;(1),\dots$ and then let us write matrix product $A\equiv A^{(0)}=L^{(0)}U^{(0)}$ in such way that these rows and columns are separated from the rest.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Namely it turns out that one can multiply matrix blocks in such way as if they were ordinary numbers, i.e. row times column, except that now their components are sub-matrices, sometimes reduced to scalars or vectors.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Now comes the crucial observation: nothing prevents us to treat $A^{(1)}$ the same way as we did with $A^{(0)}$ , repeatedly.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If dimension of A is n × n, after *n*− 1 such steps all columns ${\bf {v}}$ form sub-diagonal part of triangle matrix L and all pivots a combined with rows ${\bf {w}}^{\textsf {T}}$ form upper triangle matrix U , as required.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In the above example *n* = 3 so only two steps suffice.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The above procedure demonstrates that at no step the top diagonal pivot element a of consecutive sub-matrices can be zero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] To avoid it columns or rows may be swapped so that a becomes nonzero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Such procedure involving permutation is called *LUP*, decomposition with pivoting.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Permutation of columns corresponds to matrix product $AQ^{(0)}$ where $Q^{(0)}$ is a permutation matrix, i.e. the identity matrix I after the same column permutation.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] After all steps such LUP decomposition applies to $AQ^{(0)}\cdots Q^{(n-1)}\equiv AQ=LU$ .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Present computation scheme and similar in Cormen et al. are examples of **recurrence algorithms**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] 2. final values of L and U matrices are obtained gradually, one row or column per step.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Recurrence algorithms are not overly costly in terms of algebraic operations yet they suffer from practical disadvantage due to need to update and store most elements of A at each step.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] It will be seen that by reordering calculations it is possible to dispose with storage of intermediate values.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] It turns out that a proper permutation of rows (or columns) to select column (or row) absolute maximal pivot *a*11 is sufficient for numerically stable LU factorization, except for known pathological cases.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] It is called ***LU factorization with partial pivoting*** (LUP): $PA=LU,\quad (AQ=LU),$ where L and U are again lower and upper triangular matrices, and P and Q are corresponding permutation matrices, which, when correspondingly left- and right-multiplied to A, reorder the rows and columns of A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] It turns out that all square matrices can be factorized in this form, and the factorization is numerically stable in practice.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This makes LUP decomposition a useful technique in practice.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] A variant called ***rook pivoting*** at each step involves search of maximum element the way rook moves on a chessboard, along column, row, column again and so on till reaching a pivot maximal in both its row and column.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] It can be proven that for large matrices of random elements its cost of operations at each step is similarly to partial pivoting proportional to the length of matrix side unlike its square for full pivoting.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] An ***LU factorization with full pivoting*** involves both row and column permutations to find absolute maximum element in the whole submatrix: $PAQ=LU,$ where L, U, and P are defined as before, and Q is a permutation matrix that reorders the columns of A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] A ***lower-diagonal-upper decomposition*** (LDU) is a decomposition of the form $A=LDU,$ where D is a diagonal matrix, and L and U are unitriangular matrices, meaning that all the entries on the diagonals of L and U are one.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Above we required that A be a square matrix, but these decompositions can all be generalized to rectangular matrices as well.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In that case, L and D are square matrices both of which have the same number of rows as A, and U has exactly the same dimensions as A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] 'Upper triangular' should be interpreted as having only zero entries below the main diagonal, which starts at the upper left corner.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Similarly, the more precise term for U is that it is the row echelon form of the matrix A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] One way to find the LU decomposition of this simple matrix would be to simply solve the linear equations by inspection.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This system of equations is underdetermined.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In this case any two nonzero elements of L and U matrices are parameters of the solution and can be set arbitrarily to any nonzero value.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Therefore, to find the unique LU decomposition, it is necessary to put some restriction on L and U matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] For example, we can conveniently require the lower triangular matrix L to be a unit triangular matrix, so that all the entries of its main diagonal are set to one.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Any square matrix A admits LUP and PLU factorizations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If A is invertible, then it admits an LU (or LDU) factorization if and only if all its leading principal minors are nonzero (for example $\left[{\begin{smallmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{smallmatrix}}\right]$ does not admit an LU or LDU factorization).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If A is a singular matrix of rank k, then it admits an LU factorization if the first k leading principal minors are nonzero, although the converse is not true.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If a square, invertible matrix has an LDU factorization (with all diagonal entries of L and U equal to 1), then the factorization is unique.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In that case, the LU factorization is also unique if we require that the diagonal of either L or U consists of ones.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] 3. no LU factorization if the first (*n* − 1) columns are linearly independent and at least one leading principal minor is zero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In Case 3, one can approximate an LU factorization by changing a diagonal entry aij to *aij* ± *ε* to avoid a zero leading principal minor.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If A is a symmetric (or Hermitian, if A is complex) positive-definite matrix, we can arrange matters so that U is the conjugate transpose of L.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This decomposition is called the Cholesky decomposition.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If A is positive definite, then the Cholesky decomposition exists and is unique.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Furthermore, computing the Cholesky decomposition is more efficient and numerically more stable than computing some other LU decompositions.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] For a (not necessarily invertible) matrix over any field, the exact necessary and sufficient conditions under which it has an LU factorization are known.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The conditions are expressed in terms of the ranks of certain submatrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The Gaussian elimination algorithm for obtaining LU decomposition has also been extended to this most general case.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] When an LDU factorization exists and is unique, there is a closed (explicit) formula for the elements of L, D, and U in terms of ratios of determinants of certain submatrices of the original matrix A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In particular, *D*1 = *A*1,1, and for *i* = 2, ... , *n*, Di is the ratio of the i-th principal submatrix to the (*i* − 1)-th principal submatrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Computation of the determinants is computationally expensive, so this explicit formula is not used in practice.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The following algorithm is essentially a modified form of Gaussian elimination.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Computing an LU decomposition using this algorithm requires ⁠2/3⁠*n*3 floating-point operations, ignoring lower-order terms.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Partial pivoting adds only a quadratic term; this is not the case for full pivoting.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Given an N × N matrix $A=(a_{i,j})_{1\leq i,j\leq N}$ , define $A^{(0)}$ as the original, unmodified version of the matrix A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The parenthetical superscript (e.g., (0)) of the matrix A is the version of the matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The matrix *A*(*n*) is the A matrix in which the elements below the main diagonal have already been eliminated to 0 through Gaussian elimination for the first n columns.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] During this process, we gradually modify the matrix A using row operations until it becomes the matrix U in which all the elements below the main diagonal are equal to zero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] During this, we will simultaneously create two separate matrices P and L, such that *PA* = *LU*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] We define the final permutation matrix P as the identity matrix which has all the same rows swapped in the same order as the A matrix while it transforms into the matrix U.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] For our matrix *A*(*n*−1), we may start by swapping rows to provide the desired conditions for the n-th column.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] For example, we might swap rows to perform partial pivoting, or we might do it to set the pivot element an,n on the main diagonal to a nonzero number so that we can complete the Gaussian elimination.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] For our matrix *A*(*n*−1), we want to set every element below $a_{n,n}^{(n-1)}$ to zero (where $a_{n,n}^{(n-1)}$ is the element in the n-th column of the main diagonal).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Once we have performed the row operations for the first *N* − 1 columns, we have obtained an upper triangular matrix *A*(*N*−1) which is denoted by U.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] We can also create the lower triangular matrix denoted as L, by directly inputting the previously calculated values of ℓi,n via the formula below.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Now these matrices have a relation such that *PA* = *LU*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Now let's compute the sequence of *L*1 ⋯ *L**N*−1.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If there are two lower triangular matrices with 1s in the main diagonal, and neither have a nonzero item below the main diagonal in the same column as the other, then we can include all nonzero items at their same location in the product of the two matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Finally, multiply L1 together and generate the fused matrix denoted as L (as previously mentioned).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Using the matrix L, we obtain *A* = *LU*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] It is clear that in order for this algorithm to work, one needs to have $a_{n,n}^{(n-1)}\neq 0$ at each step (see the definition of ℓi,n.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If this assumption fails at some point, one needs to interchange n-th row with another row below it before continuing.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This is why an LU decomposition in general looks like *P*−1*A* = *LU*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The peculiar matrix notation used by Banachiewicz enabled him to multiply matrices column by column, a convenient feature for mechanical calculations as he could reveal consecutive factors by sliding a ruler to next rows of matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] For human readers however, his equations are best transformed into standard matrix notation.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] To obtain from a full matrix A triangle matrices U and L calculations, start by copying top row and leftmost column of A respectively into corresponding positions of matrices U and L.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The known unit diagonal elements of L are not stored nor used throughout the whole process.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Next calculations continue for the subsequent rows and columns till the bottom right corner of A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The figure illustrates calculations for 3rd row and column, assuming previous stages were already completed.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Involved matrices are named above squares marking their content.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Matrix products and subtractions are applied only to elements in the thick frame boxes.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Green filled thin frame boxes indicate values already known, from previous stages.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Blue boxes indicate places in U and L matrices for storing of results.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Note that at each stage the result elements of L need to be divided by the corresponding pivot element on the main diagonal of U.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This applies to the leftmost column of L too.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Note that after completion of 3rd stage the involved elements of matrix A are no longer used and neither those from the previous stages.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This enables replacement of these elements with the result values of U and L, i.e. execution of LU decomposition *in place*, so that the whole A is replaced with U and L except for the unit diagonal of L.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Banachiewicz LU algorithm is well suited for partial pivoting by choosing the absolute maximum pivot from the newly calculated row of U and subsequently swapping its columns so that it lands on the main diagonal.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] More details can be figured out from inspection of the enclosed Fortran90 code.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] All partial pivoting LU algorithms cost roughly the same amount, of order ${\textstyle O\left({2 \over 3}n^{3}\right)}$ operations, where n is the number of rows or columns of A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Note that the decomposition obtained through this procedure is a **Doolittle decomposition**: the main diagonal of L is composed solely of ones.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If one would proceed by removing elements *above* the main diagonal by adding multiples of the *columns* (instead of removing elements *below* the diagonal by adding multiples of the *rows*), we would obtain a *Crout decomposition*, where the main diagonal of U is of ones.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Another (equivalent) way of producing a Crout decomposition of a given matrix A is to obtain a Doolittle decomposition of the transpose of A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Indeed, if *A*T = *L*0*U*0 is the LU-decomposition obtained through the algorithm presented in this section, then by taking *L* = *U*T 0 and *U* = *L*T 0, we have that *A* = *LU* is a Crout decomposition.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] It is possible to find a low rank approximation to an LU decomposition using a randomized algorithm.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] If two matrices of order n can be multiplied in time *M*(*n*), where *M*(*n*) ≥ *n**a* for some *a* > 2, then an LU-decomposition can be computed in time O(*M*(*n*)).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This means, for example, that an O(*n*2.376) algorithm exists based on the Coppersmith–Winograd algorithm.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] See also for fast matrix multiplication algorithms article for more details.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Special algorithms have been developed for factorizing large sparse matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] These algorithms attempt to find sparse factors L and U.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Ideally, the cost of computation is determined by the number of nonzero entries, rather than by the size of the matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] These algorithms use the freedom to exchange rows and columns to minimize fill-in (entries that change from an initial zero to a nonzero value during the execution of an algorithm).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] General treatment of orderings that minimize fill-in can be addressed using graph theory.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] we want to solve the equation for **x**, given A and **b**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Suppose we have already obtained the LUP decomposition of A such that *PA* = *LU*, so *LU***x** = *P***b**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In both cases we are dealing with triangular matrices (L and U), which can be solved directly by forward and backward substitution without using the Gaussian elimination process (however we do need this process or equivalent to compute the LU decomposition itself).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The above procedure can be repeatedly applied to solve the equation multiple times for different **b**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In this case it is faster (and more convenient) to do an LU decomposition of the matrix A once and then solve the triangular matrices for the different **b**, rather than using Gaussian elimination each time.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The matrices L and U could be thought to have "encoded" the Gaussian elimination process.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The cost of solving a system of linear equations is approximately ⁠2/3⁠*n*3 floating-point operations if the matrix A has size n.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This makes it twice as fast as algorithms based on QR decomposition, which costs about ⁠4/3⁠*n*3 floating-point operations when Householder reflections are used.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] For this reason, LU decomposition is usually preferred.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] When solving systems of equations, **b** is usually treated as a vector with a length equal to the height of matrix A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] We can use the same algorithm presented earlier to solve for each column of matrix X.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Now suppose that B is the identity matrix of size n, In.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] It follows that the result X must be the inverse of A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The second equation follows from the fact that the determinant of a triangular matrix is simply the product of its diagonal entries, and that the determinant of a permutation matrix is equal to (−1)*S* where S is the number of row exchanges in the decomposition.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] In the case of LU decomposition with full pivoting, det(*A*) also equals the right-hand side of the above equation, if we let S be the total number of row and column exchanges.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The same method readily applies to LU decomposition by setting P equal to the identity matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The LU decomposition is related to elimination of linear systems of equations, as e.g. described by Ralston.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The solution of N linear equations in N unknowns by elimination was already known to ancient Chinese.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Before Gauss many mathematicians in Eurasia were performing and perfecting it yet as the method became relegated to school grade, few of them left any detailed descriptions.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Thus the name Gaussian elimination is only a convenient abbreviation of a complex history.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] The Polish astronomer Tadeusz Banachiewicz introduced the LU decomposition in 1938.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Banachiewicz was the first to consider elimination in terms of matrices and in this way formulated LU decomposition, as demonstrated by his graphic illustration.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] His calculations follow ordinary matrix ones, yet notation deviates in that he preferred to write one factor transposed, to be able to multiply them mechanically column by column, by sliding ruler down consecutive rows of both (using arithmometer).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] where *IA* → *A*T; **x** ≡ [*x*1, ... , *xn*, −1]; *A*′ refers to A extended with the last column; and the last component of **x** is −1.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] Matrix formulae to calculate rows and columns of LU factors by recursion are given in the remaining part of Banachiewicz's paper as Eq.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] This paper by Banachiewicz contains both derivation of LU and *R*T*R* factors of respectively non-symmetric and symmetric matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/lu-decomposition] They are sometimes confused as later publications tend to tie his name solely with the rediscovery of Cholesky decomposition.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] The **pivot** or **pivot element** is the element of a matrix, or an array, which is selected first by an algorithm (e.g.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Gaussian elimination, simplex algorithm, etc.), to do certain calculations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] In the case of matrix algorithms, a pivot entry is usually required to be at least distinct from zero, and often distant from it; in this case finding this element is called **pivoting**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Pivoting may be followed by an interchange of rows or columns to bring the pivot to a fixed position and allow the algorithm to proceed successfully, and possibly to reduce round-off error.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] It is often used for verifying row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Pivoting might be thought of as swapping or sorting rows or columns in a matrix, and thus it can be represented as multiplication by permutation matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] However, algorithms rarely move the matrix elements because this would cost too much time; instead, they just keep track of the permutations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Overall, pivoting adds more operations to the computational cost of an algorithm.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] These additional operations are sometimes necessary for the algorithm to work at all.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Other times these additional operations are worthwhile because they add numerical stability to the final result.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] In the case of Gaussian elimination, the algorithm requires that pivot elements not be zero.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Interchanging rows or columns in the case of a zero pivot element is necessary.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] The system below requires the interchange of rows 2 and 3 to perform elimination.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] The system that results from pivoting is as follows and will allow the elimination algorithm and backwards substitution to output the solution to the system.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Furthermore, in Gaussian elimination it is generally desirable to choose a pivot element with large absolute value.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] The following system is dramatically affected by round-off error when Gaussian elimination and backwards substitution are performed.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] This system has the exact solution of *x*1 = 10.00 and *x*2 = 1.000, but when the elimination algorithm and backwards substitution are performed using four-digit arithmetic, the small value of *a*11 causes small round-off errors to be propagated.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] The algorithm without pivoting yields the approximation of *x*1 ≈ 9873.3 and *x*2 ≈ 4.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Considering this system, the elimination algorithm and backwards substitution using four-digit arithmetic yield the correct values *x*1 = 10.00 and *x*2 = 1.000.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] In **partial pivoting**, the algorithm selects the entry with largest absolute value from the column of the matrix that is currently being considered as the pivot element.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] More specifically, when reducing a matrix to row echelon form, partial pivoting swaps rows before the column's row reduction to make the pivot element have the largest absolute value compared to the elements below in the same column.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Partial pivoting is generally sufficient to adequately reduce round-off error.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] However, for certain systems and algorithms, **complete pivoting** (or maximal pivoting) may be required for acceptable accuracy.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Complete pivoting interchanges both rows and columns in order to use the largest (by absolute value) element in the matrix as the pivot.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Complete pivoting is usually not necessary to ensure numerical stability and, due to the additional cost of searching for the maximal element, the improvement in numerical stability that it provides is typically outweighed by its reduced efficiency for all but the smallest matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Another strategy, known as **rook pivoting** also interchanges both rows and columns but only guarantees that the chosen pivot is simultaneously the largest possible entry in its row and the largest possible entry in its column, as opposed to the largest possible in the entire remaining submatrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] When implemented on serial computers this strategy has expected cost of only about three times that of partial pivoting and is therefore cheaper than complete pivoting.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Rook pivoting has been proved to be more stable than partial pivoting both theoretically and in practice.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] A variation of the partial pivoting strategy is scaled pivoting.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] In this approach, the algorithm selects as the pivot element the entry that is largest relative to the entries in its row.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] This strategy is desirable when entries' large differences in magnitude lead to the propagation of round-off error.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Scaled pivoting should be used in a system like the one below where a row's entries vary greatly in magnitude.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] In the example below, it would be desirable to interchange the two rows because the current pivot element 30 is larger than 5.291 but it is relatively small compared with the other entries in its row.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Without row interchange in this case, rounding errors will be propagated as in the previous example.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] A pivot position in a matrix, A, is a position in the matrix that corresponds to a row–leading 1 in the reduced row echelon form of A.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Since the reduced row echelon form of A is unique, the pivot positions are uniquely determined and do not depend on whether or not row interchanges are performed in the reduction process.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/pivot-element] Also, the pivot of a row must appear to the right of the pivot in the above row in row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] In linear algebra, a matrix is in **row echelon form** if it can be obtained as the result of Gaussian elimination.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] Every matrix can be put in row echelon form by applying a sequence of elementary row operations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] The term *echelon* comes from the French *échelon* ("level" or step of a ladder), and refers to the fact that the nonzero entries of a matrix in row echelon form look like the steps of a staircase.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] For square matrices, an upper triangular matrix with nonzero entries on the diagonal is in row echelon form, and a matrix in row echelon form is (weakly) upper triangular.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] Thus, the row echelon form can be viewed as a generalization of upper triangular form for rectangular matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] A matrix is in **reduced row echelon form** if it is in row echelon form, with the additional property that the first nonzero entry of each row is equal to 1 and is the only nonzero entry of its column.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] The reduced row echelon form of a matrix is unique and does not depend on the sequence of elementary row operations that is used to obtain it.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] The specific type of Gaussian elimination that transforms a matrix to reduced row echelon form is sometimes called Gauss–Jordan elimination.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] A matrix is in **column echelon form** if its transpose is in row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] Since all properties of column echelon forms can therefore immediately be deduced from the corresponding properties of row echelon forms, only row echelon forms are considered in the remainder of the article.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] Some texts add the condition that the leading coefficient must be 1 while others require this only in reduced row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] These two conditions imply that all entries in a column below a leading coefficient are zeros.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] Many properties of matrices may be easily deduced from their row echelon form, such as the rank and the kernel.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] While a matrix may have several echelon forms, its reduced echelon form is unique.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] where I is the identity matrix of dimension j equal to the rank of the entire matrix, X is a matrix with j rows and $n-j$ columns, and the two 0's are zero matrices of appropriate size.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] Since a permutation of columns is not a row operation, the resulting matrix is inequivalent under elementary row operations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] In the Gaussian elimination method, this corresponds to a permutation of the unknowns in the original linear system that allows a linear parametrization of the row space, in which the first j coefficients are unconstrained, and the remaining $n-j$ are determined as linear combinations of these.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] A system of linear equations is said to be in *row echelon form* if its augmented matrix is in row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] Similarly, a system of linear equations is said to be in *reduced row echelon form* or in *canonical form* if its augmented matrix is in reduced row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] The canonical form may be viewed as an explicit solution of the linear system.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] In fact, the system is inconsistent if and only if one of the equations of the canonical form is reduced to 0 = 1; that is if there is a leading 1 in the column of the constant terms.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] Otherwise, regrouping in the right hand side all the terms of the equations but the leading ones, expresses the variables corresponding to the pivots as constants or linear functions of the other variables, if any.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] Gaussian elimination is the main algorithm for transforming every matrix into a matrix in row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] A variant, sometimes called Gauss–Jordan elimination produces a reduced row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] Both consist of a finite sequence of elementary row operations; the number of required elementary row operations is at most mn for an m-by-n matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] For a given matrix, despite the row echelon form not being unique, all row echelon forms, including the reduced row echelon form, have the same number of zero rows and the pivots are located in the same positions.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] For a matrix with integer coefficients, the Hermite normal form is a row echelon form that can be calculated without introducing any denominator, by using Euclidean division or Bézout's identity.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] The reduced echelon form of a matrix with integer entries generally contains non-integer entries, because of the need to divide by its leading coefficient each row of the echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] The non-uniqueness of the row echelon form of a matrix follows from the fact that some elementary row operations transform a matrix in row echelon form into another (equivalent) matrix that is also in row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] These elementary row operations include the multiplication of a row by a nonzero scalar and the addition of a scalar multiple of a row to one of the rows above it.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] where $j\leq k$ is the dimension of the row space of the matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/row-echelon-form] To see this, note that, of the $nj$ possible matrix entries within the first j rows, $j^{2}$ are determined as 0 's and 1 's because they are in the columns $(L_{1},\dots ,L_{j})$ containing the pivots.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] In mathematics, a **system of linear equations** (or **linear system**) is a collection of two or more linear equations involving the same variables.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] is a system of three equations in the three variables *x*, *y*, *z*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] A *solution* to a linear system is an assignment of values to the variables such that all the equations are simultaneously satisfied.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] In the example above, a solution is given by the ordered triple $(x,y,z)=(1,-2,-2),$ since it makes all three equations valid.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Linear systems are a fundamental part of linear algebra, a subject used in most modern mathematics.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Computational algorithms for finding the solutions are an important part of numerical linear algebra, and play a prominent role in engineering, physics, chemistry, computer science, and economics.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] A system of non-linear equations can often be approximated by a linear system (see linearization), a helpful technique when making a mathematical model or computer simulation of a relatively complex system.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Very often, and in this article, the coefficients and solutions of the equations are constrained to be real or complex numbers, but the theory and algorithms apply to coefficients and solutions in any field.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For other algebraic structures, other theories have been developed.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For coefficients and solutions in an integral domain, such as the ring of integers, see Linear equation over a ring.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For coefficients and solutions that are polynomials, see Gröbner basis.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For finding the "best" integer solutions among many, see Integer linear programming.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For an example of a more exotic structure to which linear algebra can be applied, see Tropical geometry.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] However, most interesting linear systems have at least two equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] One method for solving such a system is as follows.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This results in a single equation involving only the variable y .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Solving gives $y=1$ , and substituting this back into the equation for x yields $x={\frac {3}{2}}$ .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This method generalizes to systems with additional variables (see "elimination of variables" below, or the article on elementary algebra).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Often the coefficients and unknowns are real or complex numbers, but integers and rational numbers are also seen, as are polynomials and elements of an abstract algebraic structure.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] One extremely helpful view is that each unknown is a weight for a column vector in a linear combination.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This allows all the language and theory of vector spaces (or more generally, modules) to be brought to bear.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For example, the collection of all possible linear combinations of the vectors on the left-hand side (LHS) is called their *span*, and the equations have a solution just when the right-hand vector is within that span.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] If every vector within that span has exactly one expression as a linear combination of the given left-hand vectors, then any solution is unique.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] In any event, the span has a basis of linearly independent vectors that do guarantee exactly one expression; and the number of vectors in that basis (its dimension) cannot be larger than *m* or *n*, but it can be smaller.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This is important because if we have *m* independent vectors a solution is guaranteed regardless of the right-hand side (RHS), and otherwise not guaranteed.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The vector equation is equivalent to a matrix equation of the form $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ where *A* is an *m*×*n* matrix, **x** is a column vector with *n* entries, and **b** is a column vector with *m* entries.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] A *solution* of a linear system is an assignment of values to the variables $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}$ such that each of the equations is satisfied.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The set of all possible solutions is called the *solution set*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For a system involving two variables (*x* and *y*), each linear equation determines a line on the *xy*-plane.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Because a solution to a linear system must satisfy all of the equations, the solution set is the intersection of these lines, and is hence either a line, a single point, or the empty set.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For three variables, each linear equation determines a plane in three-dimensional space, and the solution set is the intersection of these planes.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Thus the solution set may be a plane, a line, a single point, or the empty set.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For *n* variables, each linear equation determines a hyperplane in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The solution set is the intersection of these hyperplanes, and is a flat, which may have any dimension lower than *n*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] In general, the behavior of a linear system is determined by the relationship between the number of equations and the number of unknowns.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Here, "in general" means that a different behavior may occur for specific values of the coefficients of the equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] In the first case, the dimension of the solution set is, in general, equal to *n* − *m*, where *n* is the number of variables and *m* is the number of equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The first system has infinitely many solutions, namely all of the points on the blue line.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The second system has a single unique solution, namely the intersection of the two lines.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The third system has no solutions, since the three lines share no common point.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] It must be kept in mind that the pictures above show only the most common case (the general case).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] It is possible for a system of two equations and two unknowns to have no solution (if the two lines are parallel), or for a system of three equations and two unknowns to be solvable (if the three lines intersect at a single point).
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] A system of linear equations behave differently from the general case if the equations are *linearly dependent*, or if it is *inconsistent* and has no more equations than unknowns.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The equations of a linear system are **independent** if none of the equations can be derived algebraically from the others.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] When the equations are independent, each equation contains new information about the variables, and removing any of the equations increases the size of the solution set.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For linear equations, logical independence is the same as linear independence.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] are not independent — they are the same equation when scaled by a factor of two, and they would produce identical graphs.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This is an example of equivalence in a system of linear equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] are not independent, because the third equation is the sum of the other two.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Indeed, any one of these equations can be derived from the other two, and any one of the equations can be removed without affecting the solution set.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The graphs of these equations are three lines that intersect at a single point.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] A linear system is **inconsistent** if it has no solution, and otherwise, it is said to be **consistent**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] When the system is inconsistent, it is possible to derive a contradiction from the equations, that may always be rewritten as the statement 0 = 1.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] In fact, by subtracting the first equation from the second one and multiplying both sides of the result by 1/6, we get 0 = 1.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The graphs of these equations on the *xy*-plane are a pair of parallel lines.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] It is possible for three linear equations to be inconsistent, even though any two of them are consistent together.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Adding the first two equations together gives 3*x* + 2*y* = 2, which can be subtracted from the third equation to yield 0 = 1.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Any two of these equations have a common solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The same phenomenon can occur for any number of equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] In general, inconsistencies occur if the left-hand sides of the equations in a system are linearly dependent, and the constant terms do not satisfy the dependence relation.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] A system of equations whose left-hand sides are linearly independent is always consistent.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Putting it another way, according to the Rouché–Capelli theorem, any system of equations (overdetermined or otherwise) is inconsistent if the rank of the augmented matrix is greater than the rank of the coefficient matrix.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] If, on the other hand, the ranks of these two matrices are equal, the system must have at least one solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The solution is unique if and only if the rank equals the number of variables.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Otherwise the general solution has *k* free parameters where *k* is the difference between the number of variables and the rank; hence in such a case there is an infinitude of solutions.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Two linear systems using the same set of variables are **equivalent** if each of the equations in the second system can be derived algebraically from the equations in the first system, and vice versa.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Two systems are equivalent if either both are inconsistent or each equation of each of them is a linear combination of the equations of the other one.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] It follows that two linear systems are equivalent if and only if they have the same solution set.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] There are several algorithms for solving a system of linear equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] When the solution set is finite, it is reduced to a single element.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] In this case, the unique solution is described by a sequence of equations whose left-hand sides are the names of the unknowns and right-hand sides are the corresponding values, for example $(x=3,\;y=-2,\;z=6)$ .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] When an order on the unknowns has been fixed, for example the alphabetical order the solution may be described as a vector of values, like $(3,\,-2,\,6)$ for the previous example.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] To describe a set with an infinite number of solutions, typically some of the variables are designated as **free** (or **independent**, or as **parameters**), meaning that they are allowed to take any value, while the remaining variables are **dependent** on the values of the free variables.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Here *z* is the free variable, while *x* and *y* are dependent on *z*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Any point in the solution set can be obtained by first choosing a value for *z*, and then computing the corresponding values for *x* and *y*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Each free variable gives the solution space one degree of freedom, the number of which is equal to the dimension of the solution set.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For example, the solution set for the above equation is a line, since a point in the solution set can be chosen by specifying the value of the parameter *z*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] An infinite solution of higher order may describe a plane, or higher-dimensional set.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Different choices for the free variables may lead to different descriptions of the same solution set.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Here *x* is the free variable, and *y* and *z* are dependent.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The simplest method for solving a system of linear equations is to repeatedly eliminate variables.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Substitute this expression into the remaining equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This yields a system of equations with one fewer equation and unknown.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Repeat steps 1 and 2 until the system is reduced to a single linear equation.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Solve this equation, and then back-substitute until the entire solution is found.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Since the LHS of both of these equations equal *y*, equating the RHS of the equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Substituting *z* = 2 into the second or third equation gives *y* = 8, and the values of *y* and *z* into the first equation yields *x* = −15.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Therefore, the solution set is the ordered triple $(x,y,z)=(-15,8,2)$ .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This matrix is then modified using elementary row operations until it reaches reduced row echelon form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] : Add to one row a scalar multiple of another.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Because these operations are reversible, the augmented matrix produced always represents a linear system that is equivalent to the original.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] There are several specific algorithms to row-reduce an augmented matrix, the simplest of which are Gaussian elimination and Gauss–Jordan elimination.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The last matrix is in reduced row echelon form, and represents the system *x* = −15, *y* = 8, *z* = 2.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] A comparison with the example in the previous section on the algebraic elimination of variables shows that these two methods are in fact the same; the difference lies in how the computations are written down.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For each variable, the denominator is the determinant of the matrix of coefficients, while the numerator is the determinant of a matrix in which one column has been replaced by the vector of constant terms.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Though Cramer's rule is important theoretically, it has little practical value for large matrices, since the computation of large determinants is somewhat cumbersome.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] (Indeed, large determinants are most easily computed using row reduction.) Further, Cramer's rule has very poor numerical properties, making it unsuitable for solving even small systems reliably, unless the operations are performed in rational arithmetic with unbounded precision.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] If the equation system is expressed in the matrix form $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ , the entire solution set can also be expressed in matrix form.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] where $\mathbf {w}$ is a vector of free parameters that ranges over all possible *n*×1 vectors.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] If the condition holds, the system is consistent and at least one solution exists.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] as previously stated, where $\mathbf {w}$ has completely dropped out of the solution, leaving only a single solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] In other cases, though, $\mathbf {w}$ remains and hence an infinitude of potential values of the free parameter vector $\mathbf {w}$ give an infinitude of solutions of the equation.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] While systems of three or four equations can be readily solved by hand (see Cracovian), computers are often used for larger systems.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The standard algorithm for solving a system of linear equations is based on Gaussian elimination with some modifications.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Firstly, it is essential to avoid division by small numbers, which may lead to inaccurate results.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This can be done by reordering the equations if necessary, a process known as *pivoting*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Secondly, the algorithm does not exactly do Gaussian elimination, but it computes the LU decomposition of the matrix *A*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This is mostly an organizational tool, but it is much quicker if one has to solve several systems with the same matrix *A* but different vectors **b**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] If the matrix *A* has some special structure, this can be exploited to obtain faster or more accurate algorithms.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For instance, systems with a symmetric positive definite matrix can be solved twice as fast with the Cholesky decomposition.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Levinson recursion is a fast method for Toeplitz matrices.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Special methods exist also for matrices with many zero elements (so-called sparse matrices), which appear often in applications.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] A completely different approach is often taken for very large systems, which would otherwise take too much time or memory.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] The idea is to start with an initial approximation to the solution (which does not have to be accurate at all), and to change this approximation in several steps to bring it closer to the true solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Once the approximation is sufficiently accurate, this is taken to be the solution to the system.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This leads to the class of iterative methods.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] For some sparse matrices, the introduction of randomness improves the speed of the iterative methods.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] One example of an iterative method is the Jacobi method, where the matrix A is split into its diagonal component D and its non-diagonal component $L+U$ .
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] An initial guess ${\mathbf {x}}^{(0)}$ is used at the start of the algorithm.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] When the difference between guesses ${\mathbf {x}}^{(k)}$ and ${\mathbf {x}}^{(k+1)}$ is sufficiently small, the algorithm is said to have *converged* on the solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] There is also a quantum algorithm for linear systems of equations.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] where *A* is an *m* × *n* matrix, **x** is a column vector with *n* entries, and **0** is the zero vector with *m* entries.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Every homogeneous system has at least one solution, known as the *zero* (or *trivial*) solution, which is obtained by assigning the value of zero to each of the variables.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] If the system has a non-singular matrix (det(*A*) ≠ 0) then it is also the only solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] If the system has a singular matrix then there is a solution set with an infinite number of solutions.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] If **u** is a vector representing a solution to a homogeneous system, and *r* is any scalar, then *r***u** is also a solution to the system.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] These are exactly the properties required for the solution set to be a linear subspace of **R***n*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] In particular, the solution set to a homogeneous system is the same as the null space of the corresponding matrix *A*.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Geometrically, this says that the solution set for *A***x** = **b** is a translation of the solution set for *A***x** = **0**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] Specifically, the flat for the first system can be obtained by translating the linear subspace for the homogeneous system by the vector **p**.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This reasoning only applies if the system *A***x** = **b** has at least one solution.
[src:gaussian-elimination-algo/system-of-linear-equations] This occurs if and only if the vector **b** lies in the image of the linear transformation *A*.
